    },
    {
      "start": 54.1,
      "end": 64.7,
      "text": "Because when you succeed, they succeed. Old National Bank, where relationships and results meet. Connect with a banker today at oldnational.com slash commercial banking. Member FDIC."
    },
    {
      "start": 71.8,
      "end": 96.4,
      "text": "I'm joined by Crain's commercial real estate reporter, Rachel Herzog, here to talk about apartments. Lots of apartment things to talk about. So welcome back to the podcast, Rachel. Hi, Amy. Thanks so much for having me. Of course. So let's start by talking about this O'Hare area complex. It sold for $167 million, and that is among the priciest apartment deals this year, but there is a nuance to it. Tell me about that."
    },
    {
      "start": 96.8,
      "end": 119.6,
      "text": "Yeah, so the news today is that Chicago-based real estate firm RIG Capital paid $167 million for the Pavilion Apartments. It's on Chicago's far northwest side, just within city limits, across the street from Rosemont. So, you know, it's basically comparable to other suburban apartment complexes, more of a similar property type to those, versus downtown high-rises."
    },
    {
      "start": 120.6,
      "end": 142.0,
      "text": "Word in the suburbs, it would be a record for the priciest suburban apartment deal, but it's in city limits, so I can't technically call it that. But it is the priciest local apartment deal or the most paid for a single apartment complex so far in 2026. So we can say that. And it's up against that record, though, right? Chicago's is $175 million for a tower."
    },
    {
      "start": 142.6,
      "end": 169.9,
      "text": "So that's the priciest, I think, in two or three years, but I think the record is actually over $200 million, but it's been a few years since that. Okay, so that's a recent record. Then you noted in reporting that the suburban record is about $148 million. So that's, it's an interesting building location-wise. It's kind of in between city and suburbs, but also price-wise, right? It kind of falls in that zone. Right, right. You could say it's a suburban asset with a Chicago address."
    },
    {
      "start": 170.6,
      "end": 190.7,
      "text": "I like that. That's a much easier way to say that than what I did. All right. Tell me about the property and its purchase. Right. So this is one of the largest properties in the area. It's 1,115 units. It's kind of what's known as naturally affordable or workforce housing, meaning the rents fall. This is not a luxury building. The rents fall a little bit."
    },
    {
      "start": 191.0,
      "end": 216.5,
      "text": "below, I think, the median net rent for the suburbs. So they're not subsidized, but a little bit more within reach for people. So it went up for sale back in 2023. The seller is Brookfield Asset Management, you know, real estate giant. And they acquired it back in 2018 through a $6.8 billion acquisition of another realty trust. Right. And so they assumed the whole portfolio and that was part of it."
    },
    {
      "start": 216.7,
      "end": 223.7,
      "text": "Right, right. So we don't have their individual part of the thing or what they paid for it in that deal. What does median net rent look like in the suburbs right now?"
    },
    {
      "start": 224.0,
      "end": 251.4,
      "text": "Yeah, so the suburbs have seen pretty steady rent growth. The median net rent in the fourth quarter of 2025 was up 2.6% year over year. According to Integra Realty Resources, it rose to $2.15 per square foot. So that's kind of in line with what we've seen with suburban rent growth the past few years. You know, not as much as downtown rents. I think the suburbs are seeing a little more development, but it is still kind of constrained due to kind of financing and broader factors. So definitely a"
    },
    {
      "start": 251.7,
      "end": 279.4,
      "text": "supply and demand dynamic that appeals to investors. Yeah, definitely. Well, in other apartment news, talk to me about the Chicago firm that has paid $91 million for Cain County Apartments. Right. So we had news about another high dollar deal yesterday. Insonia Properties, which I believe is a local firm, paid about $91 million for the 352-unit villages at Canterfield. So that's in the far northwest suburbs in West Dundee."
    },
    {
      "start": 279.9,
      "end": 303.2,
      "text": "Definitely among the first major suburban rental property sales of 2026, we saw a $102 million sale out of Orland Ridge back in March, and then there was the $110 million sale of a complex in Crest Hill in the southwest suburbs in January. So we've seen a few of these sales. And how do these compare to the last property that we were talking about that you described as workforce housing?"
    },
    {
      "start": 303.7,
      "end": 332.5,
      "text": "Yeah, based on my understanding, this is kind of a similar type of asset known as workforce housing. And Sonia Properties said on LinkedIn that, you know, their investment strategy properties they buy includes, quote, deepening affordability for working families. So the rents at this complex are a little bit below the median net rent in the overall Chicago suburbs, as we talked about. They also said in their LinkedIn post that they plan to, quote, enhance operations through targeted capital improvements. So that indicates that they're probably planning."
    },
    {
      "start": 334.1,
      "end": 345.4,
      "text": "Yeah, definitely. And then let's go to Elmhurst. Talk to me about these apartments that have sold to an Ohio pension fund for $85 million."
    },
    {
      "start": 345.9,
      "end": 372.5,
      "text": "Right, so the State Teachers Retirement System of Ohio paid $85 million for an apartment property known as The Finn. It's in downtown Elmhurst. But what's actually interesting about this deal is the seller. They're an apartment development firm known as Cartera, which is part of national home builder, Lenar. And Cartera's kind of been, you know, reevaluating their apartment portfolio. They've listed and sold quite a few apartment buildings nationally."
    },
    {
      "start": 374.3,
      "end": 401.2,
      "text": "Particular sale comes a few months after global alternative asset management firm TPG acquired a majority stake in Cortera, but TPG was not a part of this deal. This deal was in the works before then, I believe. And you've put some price points in the reporting here, and these seem like they're at the much higher end of suburban apartments. Yeah, this is not what we would consider workforce housing. I think, you know, rents at this complex range from about..."
    },
    {
      "start": 401.4,
      "end": 428.9,
      "text": "Just shy of $2,000 for a studio apartment, which is kind of comparable to what you might see downtown. So these are in downtown Elmhurst near the Metro Station, you know, very desirable area. This is, you know, a top of the line apartment building with, you know, Class A, all the amenities. Yeah. Well, it's been about a month or so since we've talked about apartments, but, you know, focusing in on suburban apartments, how would you, how would you characterize how that market is looking right now? Or maybe just even the Chicago area overall, not really?"
    },
    {
      "start": 429.3,
      "end": 451.9,
      "text": "You know, just focusing on suburbs. Yeah, I would say the Chicago suburbs probably don't have the, you know, big highs and lows that other markets like the Sunbelt do. You know, they've seen rent growth, but it's been, you know, kind of moderate. But I think that's probably something that, you know, appeals to certain types of investors that just want something that's, you know, they know there's going to be steady demand for these properties."
    },
    {
      "start": 452.8,
      "end": 477.5,
      "text": "In conversations about the city, we've talked about just the lack of new apartments being built. Are we seeing that same kind of constraint in the suburbs? Yeah, not quite as much constraint. I think there probably has been, you know, moderate amount of development across the suburbs. But yeah, there is some, you know, I would say it's limited new supply hitting the market in the suburbs. And another factor boosting demand that I didn't get into is, you know, people are..."
    },
    {
      "start": 477.7,
      "end": 506.0,
      "text": "still putting off home buying due to, you know, high prices, high interest rates. So they might be staying in apartments for longer and maybe paying more for rent. Right, right. Which is this crossover conversation that I have with our colleague, Dennis Rodkin, often about what's driving home buying or what's not driving home buying right now. And that's, I should have the two of you on together at the same time to just talk about the journey of housing. Indeed. All right. Well, thanks, Rachel. Always a pleasure to have you on and check in about what's going on in the market."
    },
    {
      "start": 506.4,
      "end": 515.6,
      "text": "Thanks so much, Amy. Coming up, the closure of Spirit Airlines costs Chicago hundreds of jobs. We'll talk about that and more right after this."
    },
    {
      "start": 521.5,
      "end": 548.5,
      "text": "Crain's Daily Gist listeners know their Chicago business, so why not prove it by taking the Crain's Weekly News Quiz at chicagobusiness.com. Did you keep up with the week's news? Now you can test your knowledge with our weekly quiz. Visit chicagobusiness.com slash quiz. And of course, Crain's Daily Gist is a great study guide. Follow us wherever you get your podcasts. This is the Crain's Daily Gist with Amy Guth."
    },
    {
      "start": 550.0,
      "end": 574.2,
      "text": "Governor J.B. Pritzker dismissed Chicago Mayor Brandon Johnson's latest pitch to keep the Bears in the city as too little, too late, as legislators head into the last two weeks of the spring session. This is kind of typical. The mayor has shown up every spring at the end of session to pronounce what he would like to see happen. And as you know, the budget gets put together starting in November."
    },
    {
      "start": 574.8,
      "end": 587.8,
      "text": "Governor Pritzker said Monday morning at a press conference, quote, the mayor has come up with no plan how the Bears would end up in the city of Chicago, so that's problematic. Continuing by saying, quote, I would love for them to be in the city."
    },
    {
      "start": 588.2,
      "end": 617.0,
      "text": "He also said, quote, we're three years in and he still has no plan. The Bears have said publicly they have only two options, the state of Indiana or Arlington Heights. We would like them to stay in the state of Illinois, so I'm fighting hard to make sure they can do that. John Pletz noted in reporting that the Bears saga is just the latest example of how the governor and the mayor frequently have differing agendas. Johnson, two years ago, proposed building a new lakefront stadium, getting the support of"
    }
